The translation of "Demokratie ohne Volksverbundenheit" from German to English is:  "Democracy without national unity" or "Democracy without people's cohesion"  The term "Volksverbundenheit" can have slightly different connotations depending on the context, but in this case, "national unity" or "people's cohesion" captures the essence well.
Something is democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people and is granted power by them, and this happens everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
The voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of elections for the European Parliament, the voter turnout was so low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Apart from turnout, we have come to accept parties or candidates that have received 25% of the cast votes as "winners."
From Holland to Finland and on to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed based on minority support.
The apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American Presidents were elected by more than 10% of the eligible voters. In fact, half of the eligible voters in the USA do not even register to vote; among those who do register, half do not actually vote; and less than half of those who do vote cast their ballots for the winning candidate.
Even Tony Blair's "damning" majority in the UK House of Commons is built on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only slightly over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, and this was during a time when the voter turnout was 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, elections look quite different today compared to twenty, or even fifty years ago.
What has happened?
A possible answer is that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy works in most countries due to the mediation of organizations that present candidates who campaign for certain packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "election program."
For various reasons, this time-honored practice no longer works.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages imposed by the parties, they want to grab and choose something for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized ranks of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more cliquey despite losing their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people do not want to belong to any particular party, only a minority is now playing the party game.
With this, the suspicion of the public towards political parties is not least increased because, like in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, it will be taken badly.
But without financial support from the state, the parties would have to find channels for money that are often dubious, if not actually unlawful.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades involved the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the clear decline in memberships - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for an electoral democracy.
The result is an obvious separation between visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in the parliaments, the effects of this separation affect one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that parliaments represent them and therefore possess the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, fairly independent development comes into play.
The people are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
But as voters, they have to wait before they feel the results of the election they cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy requires time not only for elections, but also for discussions and prudent consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, does not want to accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives, but each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
The "Direct Action" through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet discussion forums to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the Non-Governmental Organizations (NGOs). They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet they seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
Furthermore, of course, there is the option of completely disconnecting and leaving politics to the experts, allowing oneself to focus on other priorities in life.
The latter undoubtedly harbors the greatest risks, as it fosters the creeping authoritarianism that is a hallmark of our time.
But also the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens create a rather unstable state, because no one can anymore say with certainty how representative the prevailing opinions are.
Some want to overcome the node through more direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and followers cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There are many reasons to cling to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and to try to re-connect them more closely with the electorate.
Und yet, unpopular parties and declining voter turnout could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and breathe new life into elections and representative governments.
But that probably will not be sufficient to restore the general legitimacy that the elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the first concern of all those for whom the constitution of freedom is close to their heart must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
